# Designing 150 Ambedkar-Vision Quiz Questions on India’s Fundamental Rights (Articles 12–35)

## Executive Summary: Purpose, Scope, and Ambedkar’s Vision

This blueprint sets out a complete, pedagogically rigorous plan to author a 150-question quiz covering India’s Fundamental Rights (Articles 12–35). The quiz is designed for university-level curricula, competitive examinations, and civics classrooms. It aims to deepen comprehension of Part III of the Constitution by marrying doctrinal content with the lived realities of children and families, and by consistently grounding each item in Dr. B.R. Ambedkar’s philosophy of social democracy, dignity, and meaningful equality.

The scope follows six right-groups aligned with the constitutional architecture: Right to Equality (Articles 14–18), Right to Freedom (Articles 19–22), Right against Exploitation (Articles 23–24), Freedom of Religion (Articles 25–28), Cultural and Educational Rights (Articles 29–30), and Constitutional Remedies (Article 32; with related Articles 33–35 for contextual breadth). Each right-group receives a question quota calibrated to its doctrinal density and teaching priorities. The final distribution is: Equality (30), Freedom (35), Exploitation (20), Religion (25), Culture & Education (20), Remedies (20). The quiz will be stored in a single JSON file at data/quiz_expansion/university_quiz_fundamental_rights_150.json.

The guiding narrative integrates Ambedkar’s vision in three layers. First, dignity and equal citizenship require not merely formal equality but effective equality—particularly forDalits, Adivasis, women, and religious minorities. Second, constitutional guardrails—reasonable restrictions, procedural safeguards, and independent judicial review—are mechanisms to balance liberty with public order, morality, and health. Third, remedies transform promises into protection. Together, these layers yield a quiz that is doctrinally precise, ethically consistent, and практична oriented toward safeguarding vulnerable communities.[^1][^2]

Information gaps acknowledged in this blueprint include: the exact public source link for Article 21A in the reference set; the latest official updates on the Right to Education Act implementation status; granular jurisprudence on writs; precise quota formulas for reservations; up-to-date lists of hazardous occupations for children; district-wise child protection helplines; and explicit mapping of every question to specific Ambedkar texts or speeches. These are flagged so that educators and authors can add verifiable citations or official updates as needed during item authoring and review.[^3]

## Methodology and Source Base

The blueprint follows a structured, evidence-based method:

- Article-by-article decomposition: Each Article in Part III is treated as a doctrinal anchor. Items are written to test comprehension, application, and synthesis, progressing from recall through scenario-based reasoning.
- Ambedkar integration: Every question explicitly or implicitly connects to his philosophy of dignity, non-discrimination, inclusion, and meaningful equality. Question-stems and explanations include “Ambedkar lens” prompts that encourage reflection on protecting vulnerable communities.
- School-life and real-life scenarios: Given the educational audience, everyday contexts (classroom, playground, admission processes, school calendars) illustrate doctrinal points. This narrative method is drawn from a story-based teaching resource aligned with Part III.[^3]
- Fact-checking protocol: Item content is aligned to the official constitutional text and trusted summaries, with minimal but sufficient citations in the Explanations or References sections. Where laws intersect with constitutional Articles (e.g., child labor statutes), supporting summaries are used.
- Authoring workflow: A quality assurance (QA) pipeline checks doctrinal accuracy, Ambedkar alignment, coverage balance, bias and sensitivity review, and compliance with the JSON schema.
- JSON file handling: The quiz is stored at data/quiz_expansion/university_quiz_fundamental_rights_150.json. Authors update the file incrementally in phases, with versioning to ensure traceability.

