### Right to Equality (Articles 14–18) — 30 Questions

Items will probe equality before the law and equal protection (Article 14), the scope and exceptions of non-discrimination with special provisions (Article 15), equal opportunity and reservations (Article 16), abolition of untouchability (Article 17), and abolition of titles (Article 18). Scenario applications will emphasize public amenities, school admissions, and transparent recruitment, always asking students to articulate how the Ambedkar lens strengthens fairness for vulnerable communities.[^4][^6]

### Right to Freedom (Articles 19–22) — 35 Questions

Items will cover the six freedoms under Article 19 and reasonable restrictions, procedural safeguards under Article 20 (no ex post facto laws, no double jeopardy, no self-incrimination), Article 21 (life and personal liberty with fair procedure), Article 21A (right to education), and Article 22 (rights in arrest/detention). Scenarios involve student journalism, peaceful assemblies, science lab safety, and school relocation. Questions require students to balance liberty with public order and morality, a core Ambedkarite equilibrium.[^7][^3][^8]

### Right against Exploitation (Articles 23–24) — 20 Questions

Items will examine prohibitions on trafficking, begar/forced labor (Article 23), and child labor in hazardous occupations (Article 24), supported by statutory frameworks. Scenario applications will emphasize reporting mechanisms, school-based safety practices, and state-imposed compulsory service for public purposes under non-discriminatory conditions. Ambedkar’s insistence on dignity frames ethical reasoning across items.[^9][^10][^11]

### Right to Freedom of Religion (Articles 25–28) — 25 Questions

Items will address conscience and propagation (Article 25), denominational autonomy (Article 26), taxation neutrality (Article 27), and prohibition of religious instruction in state-funded schools with opt-in rules where endowments exist (Article 28). Scenarios will include inclusive calendars, interfaith fairs, and institutional neutrality. The Ambedkar lens highlights respect for pluralism within a secular state.[^12][^3][^13]

### Cultural and Educational Rights (Articles 29–30) — 20 Questions

Items will target conservation of language/script/culture (Article 29), non-discrimination in admissions to state/state-aided institutions, and minority rights to establish and administer institutions with non-discriminatory aid (Article 30). Scenario applications will cover library additions in community languages, fair aid distribution, and inclusive admissions. The Ambedkar lens ties these rights to substantive equality and access for historically excluded groups.[^14][^15]

### Right to Constitutional Remedies (Article 32; with 33–35) — 20 Questions

Items will focus on the Supreme Court’s writ jurisdiction (Article 32) and the five writs—habeas corpus, mandamus, prohibition, certiorari, quo warranto—plus contextual awareness of Articles 33–35 (service modifications, martial law, punishment for violations of Part III). Scenarios will involve illegal detention, duty-bound government actions, jurisdictional errors, and public interest litigation (PIL). Questions emphasize remedies as the practical guardian of rights, in line with Ambedkar’s constitutionalvision.[^16][^1][^2]

## Ambedkar Lens Integration Framework

Each question is annotated with one or more of the following lenses, connecting doctrinal content to Ambedkar’s philosophy and priorities:

- Dignity and equal citizenship: Formal and substantive equality; no dehumanization through discrimination or untouchability.
- Non-discrimination: Active prohibition of exclusion based on religion, race, caste, sex, or place of birth; inclusive participation in public life.
- Inclusion: Affirmative measures (special provisions, reservations) to bring historically excluded communities into the mainstream.
- Safeguards: Procedural protections against arbitrary state action; balance of liberty with public order, morality, and health.
- Remedies: Judicial enforcement as the vehicle that turns promises into protections.

For illustration, Table 10 maps sample lenses to Articles.

Table 10. Sample Ambedkar Lens Mapping

| Lens | Illustrative Article | Integration Example |
|---|---|---|
| Dignity & equal citizenship | 14, 17 | School facilities shared equally; untouchability abolished in practice |
| Non-discrimination | 15, 29 | No denial of admissions based on identity; library access includes all languages |
| Inclusion | 16, 30 | Reservations in public jobs; fair aid to minority institutions |
| Safeguards | 19–22 | Reasonable restrictions justify balancing freedoms with safety |
| Remedies | 32 | Writs to stop illegal school exclusions or unlawful detention[^1][^2][^3] |

Authors embed these lenses in question stems, options (for MCQs), and explanations to ensure that ethical reasoning is explicit alongside doctrinal accuracy.

## Question Types, Difficulty Gradient, and Cognitive Distribution

The quiz includes multiple item types to assess knowledge, comprehension, application, and synthesis:

- Multiple Choice Questions (MCQ): Four options with one best answer.
- Short Answer Questions (SAQ): One to three sentences focusing on doctrinal definitions or reasoned application.
- Scenario-based Items: Everyday situations demanding identification of the relevant Article and analysis of boundaries or remedies.

Table 11 sets the cognitive level distribution across right-groups; Table 12 defines type-specific formatting guidance.

Table 11. Cognitive Level Distribution by Right-Group (150 Items)

| Right-Group | Remember | Understand | Apply | Analyze/Evaluate | Total |
|---|---:|---:|---:|---:|---:|
| Equality | 6 | 9 | 10 | 5 | 30 |
| Freedom | 7 | 11 | 12 | 5 | 35 |
| Exploitation | 4 | 6 | 7 | 3 | 20 |
| Religion | 5 | 8 | 9 | 3 | 25 |
| Culture & Education | 4 | 6 | 7 | 3 | 20 |
