Table 12. Type Definitions and Formatting

| Type | Structure | Doctrinal Anchor | Ambedkar Lens Prompt |
|---|---|---|---|
| MCQ | Stem + 4 options (A–D) | Article-specific principle | “Which option best reflects equal dignity and non-discrimination?” |
| SAQ | Short stem; 1–3 sentences | Definition/application | “Explain how this scenario protects vulnerable communities.” |
| Scenario-based | Narrative stem; multi-step | Article + guardrail/remedy | “Identify the right, its limits, and the appropriate remedy.”[^3][^8] |

Difficulty ranges from recall to higher-order analysis, with a progressive emphasis on application and synthesis in later items within each right-group.

## JSON File Format and Assembly Plan

The quiz is delivered as a single UTF-8 encoded JSON file at data/quiz_expansion/university_quiz_fundamental_rights_150.json. Each item is a JSON object with the following fields:

- id: Unique integer.
- right_group: One of {Equality, Freedom, Exploitation, Religion, Culture & Education, Remedies}.
- article: Article(s) tested (e.g., “14”, “19–22”).
- question_type: One of {MCQ, SAQ, Scenario}.
- difficulty: One of {Easy, Medium, Hard}.
- stem: The question text.
- options: For MCQ only; array of four strings A–D.
- correct_answer: Option letter for MCQ (e.g., “B”); concise key point for SAQ/Scenario.
- explanation: 2–5 sentences connecting doctrinal content, scenario, and Ambedkar lens.
- ambedkar_lens: Array of tags (e.g., [“Dignity & equal citizenship”, “Non-discrimination”]).
- tags: Array of topical tags (e.g., [“Reservations”, “Public order”]).

Naming conventions and ordering follow right-group sequences (Equality → Remedies) and article-wise ascending order within each group. Versioning is applied via incremental updates, with a changelog noting added/revised items.

Table 13 defines the JSON schema fields.

Table 13. JSON Schema Fields (Required)

| Field | Type | Allowed Values | Constraints |
|---|---|---|---|
| id | Integer | 1–150 | Unique |
| right_group | String | Equality; Freedom; Exploitation; Religion; Culture & Education; Remedies | As enumerated |
| article | String | “14”, “15”, “16”, “17”, “18”, “19”, “20”, “21”, “21A”, “22”, “23”, “24”, “25”, “26”, “27”, “28”, “29”, “30”, “32”, “33”, “34”, “35” | Article-wise grouping |
| question_type | String | MCQ; SAQ; Scenario | — |
| difficulty | String | Easy; Medium; Hard | — |
| stem | String | — | 1–3 sentences (SAQ/Scenario up to 4) |
| options | Array[String] | A–D | MCQ only; length=4 |
| correct_answer | String | “A/B/C/D” or concise key | Must match type |
| explanation | String | — | 2–5 sentences |
| ambedkar_lens | Array[String] | See lens set | At least one |
| tags | Array[String] | — | 2–5 tags |

Authors assemble items in batches by right-group, updating the file incrementally to minimize merge conflicts and preserve auditability.[^2]

## Quality Assurance and Validation

A rigorous QA process ensures doctrinal accuracy, balanced coverage, and sensitivity. The checklist below guides reviewers.

Table 14. QA Checklist

| Checkpoint | Criteria | Reviewer Notes |
|---|---|---|
| Doctrinal accuracy | Content aligned with constitutional text and trusted summaries | Flag any mis-statements |
| Ambedkar lens | Each item tagged with ≥1 lens; explanation includes ethical reasoning | Highlight missing integration |
| Coverage | Quotas met; article-wise distribution maintained per Table 9 | Note adjustments made |
| Difficulty gradient | Balanced Remember/Understand/Apply/Analyze | Ensure progression |
| Bias & sensitivity | Neutral phrasing; respect dignity across identities | Flag problematic language |
| Scenario realism | Everyday examples plausible; boundaries correctly applied | Suggest improvements |
| Citation mapping | Explanations reference sources where appropriate | Avoid excessive citations |
| Schema compliance | All fields present; correct formats; IDs unique | Run schema validation[^1][^2][^17][^16] |

QA review relies on the official constitutional text and trusted summaries, with a bias toward clarity and neutrality.[^1][^2][^17][^16]

## Risks, Constraints, and Mitigations

The following risks and constraints are anticipated. Each is paired with mitigation strategies to preserve content quality and timelines.

